      <bioghist id="aspace_9dc80afa925f9c43c37f3f8fba78a4f6">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>C. N. H. Long (1901-1970) was an English-American biochemist and physician His early research focused on metabolic processes; his later work focused on isolating and sequencing hormones produced by the pituitary and edrenal glands, with the goal of finding a cure for diabetes. Long spent the majority of his professional career at the Yale School of Medicine.</p>
         <p>C. N. H. Long was born in Wiltshire, England. He earned a Bachelor of Science degree at the University of Manchester, worked at the University College of London for two years, then attended McGill University, completing an M.D. in 1928. In 1928 he also married Hilda Gertrude Jarman. Long then began work at the University of Pennsylvania as Director of the George S. Cox Medical Research Institute, which focused on diabetes research.</p>
         <p>In 1936 Long began working at Yale. He served as Director of the Division of Biological Sciences from 1939–1942, Dean of the School of Medicine from 1947–1952, and Chair of Physiology from 1951–1964. He was the Sterling Professor of Physiological Chemistry for 31 years.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_62a960fe803295ac8f6bad9bde454891">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>C. N. H. (Cyril Norman Hugh) Long photographs. Historical Library, Harvey Cushing / John Hay Whitney Medical Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_964674a4255f20f38dab5c80c90e806e">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection includes individual and group portraits and snapshots of C. N. H. Long (1901-1970); his wife Hilda Gertrude (Jarman) Long; their daughters Diana and Barbara Long; and colleagues at the Yale School of Medicine including John P. Peters. Some photographs have identifying information written on the reverse.</p>
      </scopecontent>
